<paragraph blockId="8.[264,1323,283,1870]" box="[312,1171,363,390]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,819,363,389]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">Descriptive notes on macropterous male.</emphasis>
Size: length 
<number box="[972,1026,364,390]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="9.5">9.50</number>
, width 
<number box="[1112,1167,364,390]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.06">2.06</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[264,1323,283,1870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Colour. Dorsal side mainly brownish and black with silvery or golden pubescence. Head with two yellow spots laterally on anterior margin of eyes and yellow spot on posterior margin of head; pronotum with median yellow stripe and two lateral stripes on anterior part, pronotal lobe yellowish brown; legs and wings like in females described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[264,466,564,590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982) Semiterrestrial water striders of the genera Eotrechus Kirkaldy and Chimarrhometra Bianchi (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 9 (1), 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="1982">
Andersen (
<number box="[393,457,564,590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1982.0">1982</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Venter with silvery pubescence. Venter of head dark brown; prosternum yellow; mesosternum brownish yellow medially and dark brown laterally; metasternum and abdominal venter brownish yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[264,1323,283,1870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Structural characteristics: Head width across eyes 
<number box="[911,965,684,710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.72">1.72</number>
, head length 
<number box="[1125,1180,684,710]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.5">1.50</number>
; interocular width 
<number box="[347,402,724,750]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.64">0.64</number>
; eye kidney­shaped on dorsal view, eye size 
<number box="[995,1050,724,750]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.76">0.76</number>
. Lengths of antennal segments 
<number box="[390,437,764,790]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
: 
<number box="[459,515,764,790]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.7">2.70</number>
: 
<number box="[536,587,764,790]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.43">2.43</number>
(
<number box="[612,657,764,790]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
missing). Pronotum length 
<number box="[1023,1078,764,790]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.84">2.84</number>
. Wing venation as illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[420,623,804,830]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982) Semiterrestrial water striders of the genera Eotrechus Kirkaldy and Chimarrhometra Bianchi (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 9 (1), 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="1982">
Andersen (
<number box="[550,614,804,830]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1982.0">1982</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Lengths of mesosternum and metasternum: 
<number box="[1153,1204,804,830]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.72">1.72</number>
and 
<number box="[1263,1318,804,830]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.13">1.13</number>
. Lengths of leg segments (femur: tibia: tarsal segment 
<number box="[899,915,844,870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1.0">1</number>
: tarsal segment 
<number box="[1106,1122,844,870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.0">2</number>
) as follows, fore leg: 
<number box="[314,369,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="3.6">3.60</number>
: 
<number box="[380,436,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.85">2.85</number>
: 
<number box="[446,502,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.56">0.56</number>
: 
<number box="[512,567,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.48">0.48</number>
; mid leg: 
<number box="[681,737,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="6.5">6.50</number>
: 
<number box="[747,802,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="6.95">6.95</number>
: 
<number box="[813,869,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.45">0.45</number>
: 
<number box="[878,933,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.53">0.53</number>
; hind leg: 
<number box="[1053,1109,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="6.9">6.90</number>
: 
<number box="[1120,1171,884,910]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="8.75">8.75</number>
(hind tarsus missing); Fore femur (
<figureCitation box="[538,626,924,950]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[280,1286,791,1632]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[264,1322,752,1639]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20. Eotrechus kalidasa (male): (17) right fore leg; (18) mid tarsi; (19) abdominal venter (genitalia excluded); (20) pygophore, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174562/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[596,626,924,950]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
) simple and very slender, length about 
<number box="[1112,1178,924,950]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="13.84">13.84</number>
x maximum width (
<number box="[348,405,964,990]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="3.6">3.60</number>
: 
<number box="[418,474,964,990]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.26">0.26</number>
), ventral surface without spinelike hairs; fore tibia straight and simple, with row of long spinelike hairs on apical margin. Mid and hind femur slender and shorter than the body, with very few small black spines. Mid tarsi (
<figureCitation box="[958,1043,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[280,1286,791,1632]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[264,1322,752,1639]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20. Eotrechus kalidasa (male): (17) right fore leg; (18) mid tarsi; (19) abdominal venter (genitalia excluded); (20) pygophore, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174562/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[1013,1043,1044,1070]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
) without ventral row of spines. Claws stout, lengths of fore, mid claws 
<number box="[811,867,1084,1110]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.19">0.19</number>
: 
<number box="[878,933,1084,1110]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.21">0.21</number>
. Abdomen relatively long, length of abdominal venter from sternum 
<number box="[676,691,1124,1150]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="2.0">2</number>
to sternum 
<number box="[832,850,1124,1150]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="7.0">7</number>
: 3.00, with narrow median groove from sterna 
<number box="[343,389,1164,1190]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3–7</number>
; sternum 
<number box="[507,521,1164,1190]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="7.0">7</number>
about 
<number box="[604,656,1164,1190]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.75">0.75</number>
x length of two preceding sterna combined (
<number box="[1183,1240,1164,1190]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.68">0.68</number>
: 
<number box="[1252,1307,1164,1190]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="0.91">0.91</number>
), posterior margin slightly emarginated (
<figureCitation box="[722,809,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[280,1286,791,1632]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[264,1322,752,1639]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20. Eotrechus kalidasa (male): (17) right fore leg; (18) mid tarsi; (19) abdominal venter (genitalia excluded); (20) pygophore, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174562/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[777,809,1204,1230]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
). Genital segments and parameres (
<figureCitation box="[1228,1313,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[280,1286,791,1632]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[264,1322,752,1639]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20. Eotrechus kalidasa (male): (17) right fore leg; (18) mid tarsi; (19) abdominal venter (genitalia excluded); (20) pygophore, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174562/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[1283,1313,1204,1230]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
) matching illustrations by 
<bibRefCitation author="Matsuda" box="[562,929,1244,1270]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" refString="Matsuda, R. (1960) Morphology, evolution and a classification of the Gerridae (Hemiptera-Heteroptera). The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 41, 25 - 632." type="journal article" year="1960">
Matsuda (
<number box="[679,743,1244,1270]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="1960.0">1960</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[813,920,1244,1270]" pageId="8" pageNumber="47" value="552557.0">552, 557</number>
)
